# Angular Standards

Coding standards for Angular and TypeScript in this workspace. **Architecture** (feature layering, global state strategy between Signals and NgRx, security boundaries, bundle budgets, test runners) lives in [`angular-patterns.mdc`](angular-patterns.mdc).

## TypeScript

- **Strict type checking:** Enable and adhere to strict mode in `tsconfig` for this project.
- **Prefer type inference** when the type is obvious from context (avoid redundant annotations).
- **Avoid `any`:** Prefer `unknown` and narrow at boundaries when the type is uncertain.

Prefer inference over redundant annotations:

```typescript
// Bad
let name: string = 'Angular';

// Good
let name = 'Angular';
```

## Components and modules

- **Standalone:** Use standalone components, directives, and pipes. Avoid new `NgModule`-based features; refactor existing modules toward standalone when touching them.
- **Implicit standalone:** Do not set `standalone: true` explicitly in `@Component` / `@Directive` / `@Pipe` when it is the default for your Angular version.
- **Lazy loading:** Lazy-load feature routes to keep initial load small; avoid heavy imports in the app root unless required.
- **`NgOptimizedImage`:** Use it for static images where applicable.
- **Host bindings:** Do not use `@HostBinding` / `@HostListener`; use the `host` object on `@Component` / `@Directive` instead.
- **Single responsibility:** Keep components small and focused.
- **`input()` and `output()`:** Prefer `input()` / `output()` over `@Input()` / `@Output()` for new and heavily edited components.
- **`computed()`:** Use `computed()` for state derived from signals.
- **`ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush`:** Set `changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush` on components unless a documented exception applies.
- **Templates:** Prefer inline `template: \`...\`` for small components; use external HTML for large templates.
- **Reactive forms:** Prefer reactive forms for non-trivial flows, validation, and dynamic controls.
- **Validators and accessibility:** Sync validators with server rules where applicable. Surface errors accessibly (ARIA, `aria-describedby`).
- **Styling in templates:** Do not use `ngClass` / `NgClass` or `ngStyle` / `NgStyle`; use native `[class.foo]`, `[class]`, `[style.font-size.px]`, or `[style]` bindings.

Standalone: avoid redundant `standalone: true` when it is implied:

```typescript
// Bad
@Component({
  standalone: true,
  // ...
})
export class MyComponent {}

// Good
@Component({
  // `standalone: true` is implied
  // ...
})
export class MyComponent {}
```

`input()` / `output()` instead of decorator inputs/outputs:

```typescript
// Old decorator style
@Input() userId!: string;
@Output() userSelected = new EventEmitter<string>();
```

```typescript
// Preferred: signal-based APIs
import { input, output } from '@angular/core';

// ...
userId = input<string>('');
userSelected = output<string>();
```

Prefer native class and style bindings over `NgClass` / `NgStyle`:

```html
<!-- Bad -->
<section [ngClass]="{'active': isActive}"></section>
<section [ngStyle]="{'font-size': fontSize + 'px'}"></section>
```

```html
<!-- Good -->
<section [class.active]="isActive"></section>
<section [class]="{'active': isActive}"></section>
<section [class]="myClasses"></section>
<section [style.font-size.px]="fontSize"></section>
<section [style]="myStyles"></section>
```

## State management

- **Signals:** Use signals for local component state and reactive updates where appropriate.
- **Pure transformations:** Keep signal-derived logic as pure, predictable updates (no hidden side effects in `computed()` readers).
- **Pure updates:** Use `update()` / `set()` on writable signals—do not use `mutate()`.

## Templates

- Keep templates simple; move non-trivial logic to the class.
- **Control flow:** Prefer `@if`, `@for`, and `@switch` over `*ngIf`, `*ngFor`, and `*ngSwitch`.
- **Observables in templates:** Use the `async` pipe so subscriptions are managed automatically.

Built-in control flow:

```html
<!-- Old -->
<section *ngIf="isVisible">Content</section>
<section *ngFor="let item of items">{{ item }}</section>
```

```html
<!-- Preferred -->
@if (isVisible) {
  <section>Content</section>
}
@for (item of items; track item.id) {
  <section>{{ item }}</section>
}
```

## Lifecycle

- Avoid heavy work in **constructors**; use lifecycle hooks, `effect()`, or `computed()` as appropriate.

## Services

- **Single responsibility** per service.
- **`providedIn: 'root'`** for app-wide singletons when that matches the design.
- **`inject()`:** Prefer `inject()` over constructor parameter injection when it improves readability (e.g. in `provide` functions, `computed`, or field initializers).

Dependency injection style:

```typescript
// Constructor injection (acceptable; prefer inject() when it reads more clearly)
constructor(private myService: MyService) {}
```

```typescript
// Preferred in many cases: inject()
import { inject } from '@angular/core';

export class MyComponent {
  private myService = inject(MyService);
  // ...
}
```
